The Decline of Stop-and-Frisk through Protest and Activism

By Natasha Mathur

Stop and Frisk is a NYPD policy that was mainly started under Police Commissioner William Bratton. It was based on an idea introduced in the 1982 “broken windows” paper by social scientists James Q. Wilson and George L. Kelling. Their analysis suggested that cracking down on small crimes like vandalism would help reduce the occurence of more serious ones. The policy allows police officers to stop, question, and search people without a warrant or suspicion of a crime.

The number of stops peaked in 2011, along with public outrage about the practice. The policy was heavily criticized for the high amount of force used, the lack of evidence that it improved safety, and most importantly, the fact that most of the people stopped were black or hispanic.

Stop-and-frisk gave officers the power to detain anyone on the street, and to search them immediately. The majority of stops involved black or hispanic individuals. Further, whether a person was frisked once they had already been stopped also varied greatly based on race.

Police officers could stop people on the street for a variety of reasons, including fairly vagues ones such as “furtive movements” or “wearing clothing indicative of a crime”. While stops were inteneded to be made based on probable-cause standards, in reality the decision making was up to the officer and their supervisors. Despite the large number of people detained on the street, few weapons of any kind were found. The number of weapons found stays relatively constant even as the number of total stops varies greatly.

There was much public opposition to stop and frisk, both on the grounds that it was racist and that it did not deter crime. This manifested itself through marches, speeches, demonstrations, and journalism, as well as legal means. This culminated in a silent march from lower Harlem to then-Mayor Bloomberg’s house on the Upper East Side, demanding that Stop-and-Frisk be ended. By one year after the march the number of stops had decreased across all boroughs.

In May 2010 Officer Adrian Schoolcraft sent the Village Voice recordings that documented orders he had received to stop, frisk, and arrest black people specifically in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood. This was concrete evidence of both the goals behind the policy and how it was carried out. By the time the policy was deemed unconstitutional in August 2013 the number of stops had already greatly decreased.

Stop-and-Frisk became popular during the 1990s as a response to increased crime the decade before. However crime rates were already decreasing during that time period, due to factors such as an improved economy and more urban investment, not stop-and-frisk. The decline of the practice directly followed an increased in actiism and protest, with the legal system codifying the organizers’ impact months later.
